Lets extract the data for the functional scores. Subsetting and data types can be tricky in R. Here, we want to use the numeric values for calculations, so we use as.vector() with the parameter mode=“numeric” to get a vector of numbers.

ps1 = as.vector(ww_data$reported_effect, mode="numeric")

# We can check that we got the intended vector of numbers using the is() function
is(ps1)
## [1] "numeric" "vector"
# We can also have a look at the first row of the data frame (e.g. the first mutation)

Let’s find the average, range, sd of ps1

mean.ps1 = mean(ps1)
range.ps1 = range(ps1)
sd.ps1 = sd(ps1)

What about the means for for just mutations to alanine or just tryptophan?

just_ala = ww_data[which(ww_data$aa2 == 'A'),]$reported_effect
mean(just_ala)
## [1] -0.5286937
just_trp = ww_data[which(ww_data$aa2 == 'W'),]$reported_effect
mean(just_trp)
## [1] -0.783356

Simple plots with R’s built-in plotting machinery

Plots can be controlled at exquisite detail; for a list of all available options type par(). Par() can be invoked before calling plot() or other graphical functions to change the parameters of the plot.

?par()

Histograms

Lets make a histogram of all average log2 expression values for each reported score
hist(ps1)

?hist
hist(ps1, breaks = 20)

Let’s change this to a density histogram
hist(ps1, freq=F)

# And add the smoothed density function
lines((density(ps1)), col = "red")

Let’s make it prettier
hist(ps1, freq=F, main ="Reported mutational effects", col = "blue")

let’s make a plot with two histograms next to each other
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(ps1, freq=F, main ="Bin = Standard", col = "blue")
hist(ps1, freq=F, main ="Breaks = 25", col = "blue", breaks = 25)

Boxplots

?boxplot

Let’s make a boxplot for reported scores for alanine and tryptophan
boxplot(just_ala, just_trp, names = c("Ala", "Trp"))

# Note that if we don't reset a graphical parameter, new plots use the old parameter values

Scatterplots

Let’s look at a scatter plot of replicate 1 and 2 for the first CEU sample
plot(0:10, 20:10)

A little prettier please
plot(ww_data$reported_effect, ww_data$scaled_effect, pch = 19, xlab = "Reported effect", ylab = "Scaled effect")

We can add a line with the expected slope of 1
plot(ww_data$reported_effect, ww_data$scaled_effect, pch = 19, xlab = "Reported effect", ylab = "Scaled effect")
abline(0,1, col = "red")

Graphical output

If you want to write the results directly to a file, you can use pdf(). If you make multiple plot() calls, you will get a multipage pdf.
pdf(file="ww_reported_vs_scaled.pdf")
plot(ww_data$reported_effect, ww_data$scaled_effect, pch = 19, xlab = "Reported effect", ylab = "Scaled effect")
abline(0,1, col = "red")
dev.off()

More advanced plotting - ggplot2

Let’s make a heatmap of reported effect of each substitution at every position. To do this, we’ll use the ggplot2 package. To install it, we use install.packages(). Then, we load the package using library().

#install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)

Find a useful cheat sheet for ggplot2 here: https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/ggplot2-cheatsheet.pdf

Ggplot is based around a “grammar” of graphics. A graphic is a mapping from data to aesthetic attributes (e.g. color, size, shape) of geometric objects (e.g. points, lines, bars, etc). The graphic could also contain a statistical transformations on a distinct coordinate system. Facetting can be used to create the same plot from multiple subsets of a dataset in a systematic way. The combination of these components makes up a graphic, and the structure of ggplot is based on this idea. In ggplot, all plots consist of

data that you want to visualize a set of aesthetic mappings that describe how variables in the data are visualized layers, made up of geometric elements (e.g. geoms) that represent what you actually see on the plot scales, that map data to values in aesthetic space (e.g. a color scale, number scale, etc) faceting, which describes how to break up the data into sensible subsets (e.g. if you want scatter plot for two different conditions) themes, which specify graphical details like background color, ticking, grids, etc

A typical ggplot call will look like this:

ggplot(some_data, aes(x, y, other_global_aesthetics)) + some_geom(local_aesthetics) + other_stuff()

Ggplot’s modular structure makes it very easy to plot the same data in different ways (e.g. histogram, density plot, violin plot, boxplot).

We use geom_tile() to make a heatmap

ggplot(ww_data, aes(position, aa2)) + geom_tile(aes(fill = reported_effect)) + theme_classic()

Next, let’s make boxplots of the effect of every mutation at each position

ggplot(ww_data, aes(factor(position), reported_effect)) + geom_boxplot() + theme_classic()

Maybe we want to color each boxplot by the identity of the wild type amino acid there?

ggplot(ww_data, aes(factor(position), reported_effect)) + geom_boxplot(aes(fill = aa1)) + theme_classic()

We could also visualize the positional reported effect distributions using violin plots

ggplot(ww_data, aes(factor(position), reported_effect)) + geom_violin(aes(fill = aa1)) + theme_classic()
